2639. Fizon JEROME ALEANDER.

Vatican MS. Lat. 8075, f. 71. Ratisbon.

1 April 1532. [For the MS. and the circumstances ol' this letter sce Ep. 2038 introd.] EIDEM ERASMO

CVM Glapione non nihil mihi rubiginis intercessit ante discessum nostrum a Wormatia, quum dissentiremus de republica, sicut de rc priuata ; 011111 nepote τοῦ Ἀργεντινείου ἐπισκόπου, iam tum etiam quum Parisiis ageremus; vide igitur quam sit credendum iis quac in me dixerint 3 et tu optime nosti quam fuerit Glapionis ingenium ἀκατάληπτον καὶ δυσεπίγνωστον· quod et tu quodam in loco scri- psisti. Nam si verbis bibliopolae illius Galli, qui Venetiis agit, hominis tum suopte ingenio, tum perpetua potatione stupidi et vere bardi, vel minimam scintillam fidei habere te putarem, iam mihi Erasmus esse Erasmus desineret3 et tamen, vt colligo e non nullis tuis scriptis, non parum tibi persuasit, id quod fortasse putauit te libenter audire, me diu noctuque in tuis libris euoluendis intentum esse, vt scilicet aliquid inde elicerem quod vel scriptis meis postea improbarem, vel ad Albertum transmitterem. O meram miramque insaniam, vel meam, si id fecissem, vel multo magis tuam, si id credidistil Laborabam tum ego (quamdiu Venetiis fui) duplici quartana, et si quod mihi tempusculum inter- calaris quietis dabatur, id totum Reipublicae impendendum fuit pacique inter Caesarem, et Venetos procurandae, cuius mihi nego- cium Pontifex per literas dederat. Et potuissem semimortuus et ita occupatus istis ineptiis dare operam, a quibus et corpore et mente

2639. 1. Glapione] 111 the only letter which he wrote to Aleander which is extant (Ep. 1482) Erasmus cites Glapion and the Bishop of Strasbourg, as reporting to him that Aleander traduced him to the Em- peror. We must suppose that. in writing the letter which Aleander now answers he had again referred to these two persons, or else that Ep. 1482 was among the writings of Erasmus to which the ‘amicus qui- dam communis noster’ of l. 51 had called Aleander's attention.

2. wormatia] Glapion had been Aleander's adjutant at the Diet of

XVorms.

3. nepote] The Bishop of Stras- bourg was william of Hohenstein (see Ep. 1454. 1011). Aleander apparently means that the disagreeable things said by the Bishop were to be dis- counted by the fact that he (Aleander) and the Bishop's nephew had been on bad terms when they were at the university of Paris together.

6. quodam in loco] In the Sponyia LB. x. 1647B—F Erasmus defends himself from the charge of having disparaged Glapion.

7. bibliopolae . . . seems indicated.

Galli] Dolet
